        	<li id="comment-96635" class="zebra1">
	<p>Hi Niket. I&#8217;m glad you liked our paper. The only thing I did concerning tag spamming was looking at tag similarities that were above a certain level. As I remember I took the dice similarity measure and looked at tag connections with a similarity close to 1. At that time there were many spammers that added more or less the same tags to every bookmark. I looked up who is contributing to the found tag connection and reported those usernames to delicious and removed this tag connection in my dataset.</p>
<p>But I&#8217;m sure as soon as the service providers add this heuristic to block spam, spammers will adapt. It&#8217;s the same as with mail spam or comment spam.</p>
<p>Otis, the owner of simpy.com, does some tag spam prevention, he will surely answer some of your question. He just <a href="http://tech.groups.yahoo.com/group/simpy-user/message/615" rel="nofollow">opened the question of &#8220;user contributing to find spammers&#8221; on the simpy-user mailing list</a>.</p>
	<p><cite>Comment by <a href='http://www.pui.ch/phred/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Philipp Keller</a> &#8212; November 4, 2007 4:01 pm <a href="#comment-96635">#comment-96635</a></cite> </p>
